WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.520
Hi, so I'm a little nervous.

00:00:07.520 --> 00:00:14.120
This is my first conference talk since before the pandemic, so it's very intimidating being

00:00:14.120 --> 00:00:18.000
up here in front of all of you, not just in my living room.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:20.719
But anyways, my name is Natalie O'Shea.

00:00:20.719 --> 00:00:23.840
I am an analytics consultant at BetterUp.

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:29.799
We're a startup offering digital coaching experiences focused on helping people everywhere

00:00:29.799 --> 00:00:34.119
live their lives with greater clarity, purpose, and passion.

00:00:34.119 --> 00:00:38.799
My role on the People Insights team is to help develop and scale data-driven behavioral

00:00:38.799 --> 00:00:46.560
insights to support organizational transformation at some of the world's leading companies.

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:50.160
On our team, we're often dealing with scenarios like this.

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:56.540
So we might partner with an organization that has made major publicly announced goals to

00:00:56.540 --> 00:01:01.139
advance equity on their engineering team, for example.

00:01:01.139 --> 00:01:07.379
After years of ineffective trainings and seminars, they might turn to BetterUp as a data and

00:01:07.379 --> 00:01:13.099
science-backed solution for implementing and measuring their admirable organizational transformation

00:01:13.099 --> 00:01:14.879
goals.

00:01:14.879 --> 00:01:20.220
So in this example, they might have goals for the deployment where they want to, say,

00:01:20.220 --> 00:01:26.940
improve overall belonging for ERG leaders and underrepresented ICs while simultaneously

00:01:26.940 --> 00:01:31.800
improving inclusive leadership among managers.

00:01:31.800 --> 00:01:38.099
They might have a contract stipulation that says that we need to then map their BetterUp's

00:01:38.099 --> 00:01:44.260
whole person model to their unique cultural value competency framework.

00:01:44.260 --> 00:01:49.139
And then they want these results reported back to them at regular business reviews to

00:01:49.139 --> 00:01:53.699
track progress towards their organizational transformation goals.

00:01:53.699 --> 00:02:02.139
So this is an account you're really excited to support, but there's one major problem.

00:02:02.139 --> 00:02:07.419
You're a CSM, and you're responsible for this amazing, inspiring account, which doesn't

00:02:07.419 --> 00:02:13.500
have the support of a dedicated behavioral science expert alongside 15 other amazing,

00:02:13.500 --> 00:02:15.220
inspiring accounts.

00:02:15.220 --> 00:02:21.339
And based on our internal estimates, it takes the full account team approximately 18 hours

00:02:21.339 --> 00:02:26.619
to build a single business review, with seven of those hours dedicated to just navigating

00:02:26.619 --> 00:02:32.699
different dashboards to collect the data insights needed to demonstrate the impact that coaching

00:02:32.699 --> 00:02:38.059
is having on a partner organization's transformation goals.

00:02:38.059 --> 00:02:43.059
So rut-row, indeed.

00:02:43.059 --> 00:02:46.259
So this left our team with two crucial questions.

00:02:46.259 --> 00:02:52.460
The first being, how do we enable our field team to tell compelling stories of organizational

00:02:52.460 --> 00:02:59.100
transformation at scale with limited subject matter expert support?

00:02:59.100 --> 00:03:04.539
And once we've mastered that, how do we then productize those insights and enable our partners

00:03:04.539 --> 00:03:11.740
to have real-time insight into their own transformational goals?

00:03:11.740 --> 00:03:17.339
So apologies for the very big table here, but you guys are all data scientists, we love

00:03:17.339 --> 00:03:18.940
tables.

00:03:18.940 --> 00:03:24.419
The current patchwork of analytic tools and approaches really fails to meet our needs

00:03:24.419 --> 00:03:29.419
for scalable, self-serve reporting in a consulting context.

00:03:29.419 --> 00:03:35.419
So in-product analytics often don't address the unique customer needs, and they often

00:03:35.419 --> 00:03:40.979
lack the ability to tell a compelling story in the language of the client.

00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:46.020
While on the other side of the spectrum, ad hoc customer reporting is time-consuming and

00:03:46.020 --> 00:03:50.820
difficult to scale effectively to meet customer demand sustainably.

00:03:50.820 --> 00:03:57.580
Therefore, as companies, we often spend tons of time and money building self-serve analytic

00:03:57.580 --> 00:04:02.779
systems using business intelligence tools, but we're still left with this huge burden

00:04:02.779 --> 00:04:08.940
of effective enablement of less technical data consumers that often complain of information

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:12.020
overload, and understandably so.

00:04:12.020 --> 00:04:17.980
So at the end of all of this, we still have often simple visualizations that lack visual

00:04:17.980 --> 00:04:24.140
polish, which is not something we're particularly proud to share with our clients.

00:04:24.140 --> 00:04:30.140
One alternative code-based approach that I particularly love is parametrized reporting.

00:04:30.140 --> 00:04:36.059
This provides a much more customizable and scalable end product with professional-grade

00:04:36.059 --> 00:04:37.540
data visualizations.

00:04:37.739 --> 00:04:44.140
However, it often lacks the ability to then customize in those final stages and really

00:04:44.140 --> 00:04:49.140
tailor insights to the specific client goals and needs.

00:04:49.140 --> 00:04:54.260
So ultimately, none of these approaches quite fit the mold of what we're looking for.

00:04:54.260 --> 00:05:00.339
Instead, we want to bridge the gap between software-as-a-service and standard analytics

00:05:00.339 --> 00:05:07.179
consulting with a tool that is simultaneously scalable and easy to use, while still enabling

00:05:07.179 --> 00:05:11.140
lots of downstream tweaking and customization.

00:05:11.140 --> 00:05:16.079
More specifically, we were looking for something that lives kind of squarely between business

00:05:16.079 --> 00:05:24.779
intelligence tools like Wooker and something like code-based parametrized reporting.

00:05:24.779 --> 00:05:30.260
So through lots of user interviews, I learned that, surprise, surprise, no one really loves

00:05:30.260 --> 00:05:35.859
manually loading and taking screenshots from 10 different dashboards to build a single

00:05:35.859 --> 00:05:37.339
presentation.

00:05:37.339 --> 00:05:44.019
Instead, users wanted the convenience of self-serve tools, but also the visual polish and automation

00:05:44.019 --> 00:05:49.140
capabilities that are really only possible with more code-based approaches.

00:05:49.140 --> 00:05:52.420
So I said, por que no los dos?

00:05:52.420 --> 00:05:55.540
Let's do it.

00:05:55.540 --> 00:05:59.059
So introducing BetterUp Insights.

00:05:59.059 --> 00:06:05.859
BetterUp Insights is a shiny app that I built to enable scalable, flexible, self-serve reporting

00:06:05.859 --> 00:06:11.540
that allows members of our field team to select a reporting group of interest, whether that's

00:06:11.540 --> 00:06:19.059
a specific partner or perhaps an entire industry, which is often useful for pre-sales motions,

00:06:19.059 --> 00:06:24.540
and then generate a Google slide deck populated with various data insights, which can then

00:06:24.540 --> 00:06:30.579
be further tweaked and modified downstream to help tell a really custom, tailored story

00:06:30.579 --> 00:06:36.459
of organizational transformation in the language of the client.

00:06:36.459 --> 00:06:41.500
Just like any standard business intelligence tool, data is pulled directly from our database

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:47.660
at the time the user clicks load data, but we go one step further by not only generating

00:06:47.660 --> 00:06:52.320
professional-grade visualizations, but then directly sending those visualizations and

00:06:52.320 --> 00:06:57.799
metrics to pre-formatted Google slide decks with several different templates, including

00:06:57.799 --> 00:07:06.000
things like inclusive leadership, coaching culture, hybrid work, and manager effectiveness.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:12.700
This workflow is not only much more efficient and enjoyable, but it also greatly cuts down

00:07:12.700 --> 00:07:15.559
on opportunities for human error.

00:07:15.559 --> 00:07:21.839
So things like making sure that the date the data was pulled or end counts displayed underneath

00:07:21.839 --> 00:07:27.279
of a visualization in the caption, these may seem small, but they can make or break

00:07:27.279 --> 00:07:36.320
deals in an economic environment where every single business purchase is highly scrutinized.

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:40.399
Of course, this wouldn't be PositConf if I didn't get to geek out a little bit about

00:07:40.399 --> 00:07:43.040
the build architecture of this app.

00:07:43.040 --> 00:07:47.480
So here comes the more technical stuff, but feel free to ping me after if you want to

00:07:47.480 --> 00:07:49.660
talk more.

00:07:49.660 --> 00:07:55.380
First and foremost, I am an early and enthusiastic adopter of the Rhino framework for scalable

00:07:55.380 --> 00:07:57.920
and robust Shiny apps.

00:07:57.920 --> 00:08:03.420
So having developed several Frankenstein monolithic Shiny apps in the past myself, I knew I wanted

00:08:03.420 --> 00:08:06.459
to take a module-first approach.

00:08:06.459 --> 00:08:12.100
And while I've dabbled in other module-first frameworks like Gollum, I really prefer to

00:08:12.100 --> 00:08:16.839
keep my package development workflow separate from my app development workflow.

00:08:16.839 --> 00:08:21.160
So for me, I found the Rhino framework really intuitive and a joy to work with.

00:08:21.160 --> 00:08:27.079
So if you have a similar development mindset, I highly encourage you to check it out.

00:08:27.079 --> 00:08:30.920
Next I knew that I needed to carefully manage reactivity within the app.

00:08:30.920 --> 00:08:36.820
So beyond just making some kind of standard design choices, like making sure that we only

00:08:36.820 --> 00:08:43.080
run queries when a user clicks an action button and not just reactively when anything changes,

00:08:43.080 --> 00:08:48.599
I also adopted the R6 plus gargoyle triggers approach, which has been advocated by Juwan

00:08:48.599 --> 00:08:52.080
Hill, which I link below.

00:08:52.080 --> 00:08:57.880
I found this especially helpful because I can then embed small helper functions within

00:08:57.880 --> 00:09:03.940
the R6 object itself that allow me to do things like apply minimum data thresholds for data

00:09:03.940 --> 00:09:09.239
privacy reasons in a very easy to maintain way.

00:09:09.239 --> 00:09:14.359
And then finally, I was able to integrate much of my better app colleague Andrew Reese's

00:09:14.359 --> 00:09:19.760
previous Python workflows for working with the Google API into my Shiny app using the

00:09:19.760 --> 00:09:26.900
reticulate package, which I am fully convinced is pure magic.

00:09:26.900 --> 00:09:30.359
So what has this unlocked for our organization?

00:09:30.359 --> 00:09:36.200
The apps really become a crucial component of this emerging framework for efficient, unified,

00:09:36.200 --> 00:09:39.059
and field-tested partner reporting.

00:09:39.059 --> 00:09:49.900
So rather than just kind of willy-nilly building out product analytics, we really want to start

00:09:49.900 --> 00:09:58.460
with identifying and prioritizing that reporting need and then conducting analysis and visualizing

00:09:58.460 --> 00:10:08.539
data before we spend the time and effort really building that out into in-product data visualization

00:10:08.539 --> 00:10:09.940
tools.

00:10:09.940 --> 00:10:17.419
So in addition to just the obvious efficiency gains of this approach, one additional benefit

00:10:17.419 --> 00:10:21.820
is more strategic role alignment for our field team members.

00:10:21.820 --> 00:10:27.419
So in my initial user interviews with members of our field team, one key theme that emerged

00:10:27.419 --> 00:10:32.739
in every single conversation that I had was an overwhelming desire to lean into the more

00:10:32.739 --> 00:10:36.219
consultative elements of a sales role.

00:10:36.219 --> 00:10:40.940
So users of the app wanted to spend less time copying and pasting data from one channel

00:10:40.940 --> 00:10:47.460
to another so they could instead focus on surfacing business-relevant insights and recommendations

00:10:47.460 --> 00:10:49.119
for our partners.

00:10:49.119 --> 00:10:52.700
And maybe surfing as well, but maybe only in California.

00:10:52.700 --> 00:10:55.539
I'm in Minnesota, so no surfing for me.

00:10:55.539 --> 00:10:56.940
All right.

00:10:56.940 --> 00:11:04.500
So ultimately, BetterUp Insights was somewhat of a Trojan horse for getting our organization

00:11:04.500 --> 00:11:07.460
to adopt Posit products.

00:11:07.460 --> 00:11:12.099
And as I was telling some colleagues last night, I came into this role with admittedly

00:11:12.099 --> 00:11:14.380
a bit of an agenda.

00:11:14.380 --> 00:11:20.260
This was not my first time trying to advocate for Posit products to be procured at my company.

00:11:20.260 --> 00:11:24.840
But it was, in fact, my first time being successful in that endeavor.

00:11:24.840 --> 00:11:29.260
So I'd like to spend the remainder of my talk sharing some insights I gleaned through this

00:11:29.260 --> 00:11:33.380
process so that you might be able to take a similar approach for building the business

00:11:33.380 --> 00:11:38.500
case at Posit at your organization.

00:11:38.500 --> 00:11:44.140
So perhaps the most important insight that I gained was that you need to identify a core

00:11:44.140 --> 00:11:48.940
capability that these products will unlock for your organization.

00:11:48.940 --> 00:11:57.400
So what capability can you uniquely provide that's not already present in existing tools?

00:11:57.400 --> 00:12:01.380
So figure that out, do it, and do it well.

00:12:01.380 --> 00:12:08.020
So one pitfall that many of us, including myself, fall into is being overly enthusiastic

00:12:08.020 --> 00:12:12.979
about the full range of possibilities that you would be able to unlock if only you had

00:12:12.979 --> 00:12:14.219
Posit.

00:12:14.219 --> 00:12:20.500
So dashboards, multiple IDEs, easy API deployment, scheduled reports, just the possibilities

00:12:20.500 --> 00:12:22.900
are endless.

00:12:22.900 --> 00:12:27.780
Bring that enthusiasm here to PositConf, but save it for the boardroom.

00:12:28.739 --> 00:12:34.099
Initially, you know, instead focus on one unique capability.

00:12:34.099 --> 00:12:38.900
And that has to have a clear impact on your organization's bottom line.

00:12:38.900 --> 00:12:45.000
Equally, if not more important, build your team.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:50.179
As open source enthusiasts, we often know how to harness the power of code-based tools,

00:12:50.179 --> 00:12:54.520
but then struggle to communicate and gain buy-in from the right people.

00:12:54.520 --> 00:12:59.479
So this is why I believe that cultivating a diversity of relationships is the key to

00:12:59.479 --> 00:13:01.679
procurement success.

00:13:01.679 --> 00:13:07.400
So be Kermit the Frog, have a creative vision and no ego, recognize the unique talents of

00:13:07.400 --> 00:13:12.239
those around you, and attract your organization's weirdos.

00:13:12.239 --> 00:13:19.140
But in all seriousness, it's important not to over-anchor on any one stakeholder perspective.

00:13:19.140 --> 00:13:24.159
So for example, your business person is going to know how to best navigate your organizational

00:13:24.159 --> 00:13:32.320
hierarchy, gain buy-in, obtain resources, whereas your more engineering-minded folks

00:13:32.320 --> 00:13:36.760
are going to have a better understanding of where Posit and your specific data products

00:13:36.760 --> 00:13:41.080
are going to fit into the overall software development lifecycle.

00:13:41.080 --> 00:13:44.679
Not to mention, those people are probably the people you're going to need to tap when

00:13:44.679 --> 00:13:51.359
you actually need to get Posit up and running on your company's data infrastructure.

00:13:51.359 --> 00:13:56.119
You'll also want to develop strong relationships with your customers themselves, so the people

00:13:56.119 --> 00:14:00.960
that you are building this product with and for.

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:05.960
So I highly recommend doing extensive user interviews with these people, which is a great

00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:12.000
way not only to just clarify the problem you're trying to solve, but also simultaneously build

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:16.799
relationships and trust with your most crucial stakeholders.

00:14:16.799 --> 00:14:21.000
And if you're lucky, you'll find someone to fill every one of these roles listed here,

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:27.119
but let's be honest, it might just be you or one or two additional people that are willing

00:14:27.119 --> 00:14:29.500
to go to bat with you.

00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:32.840
In this case, it's still helpful to be aware of these roles so that you can know which

00:14:32.840 --> 00:14:37.760
hat to wear at any given time.

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:41.440
This next point is related to that core capability point at the start.

00:14:41.440 --> 00:14:46.559
So when making the case for Posit at your organization, it helps to think not in terms

00:14:47.320 --> 00:14:50.799
of what question can I answer, but what service can I provide?

00:14:50.799 --> 00:14:53.719
So i.e. create a data product.

00:14:53.719 --> 00:14:59.200
So while dashboards answer questions, data products perform valuable services, and that's

00:14:59.200 --> 00:15:03.659
ultimately what's going to get you through all of your procurement effort hurdles, which

00:15:03.659 --> 00:15:06.280
you will inevitably face.

00:15:06.280 --> 00:15:12.719
So relatedly, data products must be built with maintainability and robusticity in mind,

00:15:12.760 --> 00:15:16.760
which means that you need to think like a software engineer in order to win the war

00:15:16.760 --> 00:15:19.760
for limited software engineering budget.

00:15:19.760 --> 00:15:25.799
So all too often, I see other data scientists building scrappy prototypes and analyses with

00:15:25.799 --> 00:15:32.000
poor code practices, which is fine for an initial ideation, but if we ever intend to

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:37.159
be viewed as a real component of the product development lifecycle, we need to at least

00:15:37.159 --> 00:15:46.000
demonstrate a good faith effort at applying standard software engineering best practices.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:50.900
So things like a full continuous integration and deployment pipeline might be overkill,

00:15:50.900 --> 00:15:55.640
but just simply backing up your code in Git and at least thinking about things like dependency

00:15:55.640 --> 00:15:59.919
management should be on your radar.

00:15:59.919 --> 00:16:00.919
And I have a little...

00:16:00.919 --> 00:16:06.400
My one little rant of the day is some data scientists I've met seem to think this is

00:16:06.400 --> 00:16:10.880
overly burdensome or encroaching on their creative process.

00:16:10.880 --> 00:16:14.840
And if you feel that way, I urge you to check out a talk that I link at the bottom there,

00:16:14.840 --> 00:16:20.119
which is Science as Amateur Software Development by Richard McElrath.

00:16:20.119 --> 00:16:24.359
I think he makes a great case that it's a testament to the power of science that we're

00:16:24.359 --> 00:16:30.000
able to discern any meaningful patterns at all, given scientists' chaotic development

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:31.200
practices.

00:16:31.200 --> 00:16:37.679
So science manages to provide reliable knowledge in spite of, not because of these practices.

00:16:37.679 --> 00:16:41.200
So rant over, moving on.

00:16:41.200 --> 00:16:46.599
So my final piece of advice for anyone looking to make the case for BOSIT is you need to

00:16:46.599 --> 00:16:48.500
measure impact.

00:16:48.500 --> 00:16:53.840
So for us, this started with a baseline ROI analysis, which estimated the time cost savings

00:16:53.840 --> 00:17:01.799
for our organization to be about $1.2 million a year in time cost savings.

00:17:01.799 --> 00:17:09.040
And that was enough to make the case for better up to procure BOSIT products.

00:17:09.040 --> 00:17:14.560
But unfortunately, your journey is not over once the procurement process ends.

00:17:14.560 --> 00:17:18.199
So once installed and deployed, you'll need to continue to demonstrate the impact these

00:17:18.199 --> 00:17:20.680
tools are having on your organization.

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:26.479
So tracking usage and collecting user feedback can be a big part of that.

00:17:26.479 --> 00:17:32.239
For user feedback, that will not only help you prioritize new feature developments, but

00:17:32.239 --> 00:17:35.560
it can also just bring joy to you on a rainy day.

00:17:35.560 --> 00:17:41.959
So here are some screenshots of my colleagues' reactions when we first released Better Up

00:17:41.959 --> 00:17:45.079
Insights to the People Insights team at Better Up.

00:17:45.079 --> 00:17:50.060
So as you can see, there's a lot of joy to be had in making your colleagues' daily workflows

00:17:50.060 --> 00:17:53.380
more easy and efficient.

00:17:53.380 --> 00:17:58.819
So perhaps my favorite little nugget here was at the end of a feature enhancement request

00:17:58.819 --> 00:18:04.020
where someone signed off, thank you in advance, BOSIT obsessed.

00:18:04.020 --> 00:18:08.540
And I don't know about you, but I've never had a non-technical stakeholder call themselves

00:18:08.540 --> 00:18:10.500
Looker or Power BI obsessed.

00:18:10.500 --> 00:18:13.300
So I'm throwing a little shade there.

00:18:13.300 --> 00:18:18.859
But finally, I'd like to thank several people at Better Up that I absolutely could not have

00:18:18.859 --> 00:18:20.420
done this without.

00:18:20.420 --> 00:18:24.660
I could go on and on about them, but I'm seeing I'm at time here.

00:18:24.660 --> 00:18:27.020
And finally, Let's Connect.

00:18:27.020 --> 00:18:30.680
So you can find me on LinkedIn or Mastodon.

00:18:30.680 --> 00:18:35.380
And if you're wondering why Rihanna is on this slide, it's because if you've seen me

00:18:35.380 --> 00:18:40.260
bopping around the conference and wondered to yourself, is she pregnant or did she eat

00:18:40.260 --> 00:18:43.060
just a massive Chipotle burrito?

00:18:43.060 --> 00:18:44.500
The answer is the former.

00:18:44.500 --> 00:18:49.780
And for me, giving a talk at POSITConf is basically my nerdy equivalent of performing

00:18:49.780 --> 00:18:51.900
at the Super Bowl.

00:18:51.900 --> 00:18:53.619
So hence the meme.

00:18:53.619 --> 00:18:54.780
So that's it for me.

00:18:54.780 --> 00:18:55.780
Thank you.

00:18:55.780 --> 00:18:56.780
All right.

00:18:56.780 --> 00:18:57.780
Thank you, Natalie.

00:18:57.780 --> 00:19:08.180
I've got time for one quick question, actually.

00:19:08.180 --> 00:19:16.819
So how do you best define the necessary capability when you're trying to decide to develop?

00:19:16.819 --> 00:19:21.859
That has to be developed in discussion with your stakeholders.

00:19:21.859 --> 00:19:26.540
So you would have to know the specific problems at your organization.

00:19:26.540 --> 00:19:29.939
What are the things that are people most complaining about is what I would say.

00:19:29.939 --> 00:19:30.939
Okay.

00:19:30.939 --> 00:19:31.939
Fantastic.

00:19:31.939 --> 00:19:32.939
So know your room.

00:19:32.939 --> 00:19:32.939


00:19:38.180 --> 00:19:39.180
Thank you.

00:19:39.180 --> 00:19:40.180
Thank you.

